At a divisive party congress, prominent figures from the party’s left wing—such as Thiel, Glatzel, and Curtius—force a vote on Dingeldey’s leadership of the <span style="color: #C0A054;">**DVP**</span>. Dingeldey is ousted, replaced by zu Dohna, prompting the industrialist faction to withdraw its support and shift its funds to the right.

However, the <span style="color: #C0A054;">**DVP**</span>’s move to distance itself from its former industrial backers—and its renewed campaign to revive Stresemann’s legacy—has done much to restore some of its lost electoral strength.

Our relationship with the <span style="color: #C0A054;">**DVP**</span> has improved. Still, Dingeldey’s tenure radicalized the party toward the right, and the damage cannot be undone overnight.